GOITSEMANG TLHABYE
goitsemang.tlhabye@inl.co.za GAUTENG health has taken another step towards achieving a universal health care system for all with the launch of the first ever GP Care Cell. The care cell located in Atteridgeville, west of Pretoria was launched by Gauteng Health MEC, Dr. Gwen Ramokgopa together with the Foundation for Professional Development (FPD) and Professional Provider Organisation (PPO) Services. Through the pilot project the department and stakeholders will make use of private general practitioners to create additional HIV Testing Services and Anti-retroviral Therapy (ART) programmes. The care cell will as an addition offer programmes of drug initiation, management and retention capacity outside of public sector health facilities in a controlled manner. Numerous General Practitioners with and without dispensing licenses and community pharmacies will be organised into a network,in order to provide high quality HIV services in line with standard treatment guidelines. Ramokgopa said: “Through initiatives like the care cell we can all win and move quicker to achieving our goal to long and healthy lives for our citizens.”